<problem id="fs-idm100655456">
<para id="fs-idm66459264">A manufacturer of decorative string lights knows that 3 percent of its bulbs are defective. Using both the binomial and Poisson distributions, find the probability that a string of 100 lights contains at most four defective bulbs.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idp12030224">
<para id="fs-idm105213344">Let <emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis> = the number of defective bulbs in a string.</para>
<para id="fs-idp36557712">Using the Poisson distribution:
  <list id="fs-idm79935312" list-type="bulleted">
  <item><emphasis effect="italics">μ</emphasis> = <emphasis effect="italics">np</emphasis> = 100(.03) = 3</item>
  <item><emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis> ~ <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(3)</item>
	<item><emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> ≤ 4) = poissoncdf(3, 4) ≈ .8153</item>
</list>
</para><para id="fs-idm133149600">Using the binomial distribution
<list id="fs-idm216696064" list-type="bulleted">
<item><emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis> ~ <emphasis effect="italics">B</emphasis>(100, .03)</item>
<item><emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> ≤ 4) = binomcdf(100, .03, 4) ≈ .8179</item>
</list>
</para><para id="fs-idm98643728">The Poisson approximation is very good—the difference between the probabilities is only .0026.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>

